*Edited to add: I put the wrong date in the reel 🙈😂 The house fire happened on Jan. 4th, 2018 (not 2020 🤦🏻‍♀️)*
.
The 5th anniversary of our house fire came and went last week, with the me being the only person to remember it. (A blessing in and of itself, if you ask me!) A few years ago, I wrote a blog post about the lessons we learned from the house fire, but I feel like I can sum it up even better now. It was a turning point for our family. Suddenly, everything was in sharp focus. What was *truly* important. And that was each other.
.
Not stuff. Not career gains. Not the clout. Not money. Since that day, we’ve prioritized each other. Our extended family. Our friends. Going on adventures. Making memories. Quality family time. Date nights. We’ve embraced a slower pace of life instead of the hustle and grind that so many people seem to subscribe to these days. And it’s been such a blessing.
.
I think some people doubt me when I say our house fire was a blessing. I can see how that sounds strange 😂 Sure, it was stressful and hard while we were in the middle of it (at least for me), but so many amazing lessons and realizations came from it. I also know we were very lucky to have gotten through such an event unscathed and uninjured (the responding firefighters included) and that’s one of the reasons why we can look back on it as a blessing and not a tragedy.
.
#housefire #thebluehouse #beautyfromashes

One of my favorite cold weather treats is a steaming cup of hot wassail. It’s like being wrapped in a warm, citrusy hug and is just so comforting (especially right now when I’m a little under the weather). I like to make big batches of the mix and keep it in a glass container on our counter so I can help myself whenever I want. This is also a great treat to share with neighbors and friends - add it to small mason jars and include how much to add to a mug on the lid or a tag! 
.
One can of Tang; divided
Dry lemonade mix (to the 2 quart line on lid)
Sugar (to the one quart line on lemonade lid)
1 Tbsp cinnamon 
1-2 Tbsp vanilla extract 
1 tsp ground cloves 

Add 1/4-1/2 of the Tang to a separate bowl with 1-2 Tbsp vanilla extract to it. Using a fork or whisk, mix together until all of the dry powder is combined and no clumps are left. In a larger mixing bowl (or whatever container you plan to store the mix in), combine the rest of the Tang, lemonade powder, sugar, cinnamon and ground cloves. Add the Tang/vanilla mix to the rest of the ingredients and combine well till there’s no clumps. Scoop however much you’d like (anywhere between 2Tbsp to 1/4 C depending on your preference) into a mug, add hot water, stir and enjoy!
.

Sometimes when the world and my heart feel heavy, I like to lose myself in flowers. In creating something beautiful. After the terrible tragedy in Nashville (45 minutes from where I grew up) and a reminder of my dad’s eventual decline (from Alzheimer’s), I needed a little extra beauty. I’ve included a list of the flowers I used to make all 4 arrangements and some tips for easy arrangements.
.
Flower list (all from @traderjoes):
💐dark pink tulips
💐grape hyacinths
💐purple stock
💐chamomile
💐eucalyptus filler
.
I used a tiny vintage flower frog to help the stock and hyacinths stand up straighter in the arrangement. They’re easy to find at yard sales and estate sales - this one was $2! Also, when buying a big bunch of flowers, I try to keep in the same color family. I feel like it’s easier to make the arrangements cohesive and look nice that way without having a ton of flower arranging skills!
.

I had the idea to start a new series, a “book tour” if you will. One of my favorite items to collect (and use for my own inspiration) are design books. I typically find mine at estate sales, yard sales or thrift stores. I’ve gathered quite the collection and wanted to give y’all a little tour of some of my favorite books and the design inspiration they hold.
.
Today’s tour is The House & Garden Book of Country Rooms by Leonie Highton and published in 1997. @houseandgardenuk
.
The timelessness of so many of these rooms amazes me. They could be homes floating around on social media and in design magazines today, but were photographed almost three decades ago. My takeaways for what makes these rooms still relevant and fresh feeling are as follows (if you love country house vibes like I do 😉):
.
•A collected home will always feel inviting and interesting. Showcase the things you love and don’t be afraid to express yourself via your home.
•Pattern mixing of classics like plaids, stripes and florals paired will vintage rugs is always a good idea.
•Blue and white is timeless.
•Fresh flowers, potted plants and other natural elements bring in the “outside” and add to the relaxed, homey feel of these rooms.
•Colorwashing a room (walls, moulding, trim, doors all the same color) is nothing new and continues to be chic.
•Just like with clothing, everything old becomes new again eventually.
.
What are your big takeaways from this tour? I’d love to hear from you and if you want to peek inside more of my favorite design books! 💙💙
.
#countryhomes #countryhomestyle #upcountryhome #mycountryhome #designbook #designbooks #easttennessee #moderncountryinteriors

It’s almost black cat season! 🐈‍⬛ So, let’s chat about the history of these wee beasties for a moment. We all know the typical superstitions such as black cats crossing your path bringing bad luck and that they consort with witches or are witch familiars. But where did these beliefs and superstitions come from?
.
In ancient times, Egyptians deified black cats due to their resemblance to the cat goddess Bastet who was worshipped as a goddess of pregnancy as well as a protector against diseases and bad spirits. In the early Middle Ages, cats were seen as good luck symbols and were often found aboard ships for luck and to forecast the weather.
.
Along the way, things went sideways for cats in general. They were thought to be spreading the Bubonic plague and Europeans started wiping them out - which, ironically, only helped further the spread of the plague. In 1233, Pope Gregory IX issued the “Vox in Rama,” in which he declared that black cats were in incarnation of the devil. Thus purporting their ties to the occult. This was also the start of church sanctioned witch hunts in Europe which then caught on like wildfire. When the puritans settled in America, they brought the same prejudices and superstitions with them which ultimately led to the Salem Witch Trials.
.
Nowadays, we know that black cats aren’t actually bad luck, the devil in disguise or a shape shifting witch. But did you know black animal in general are often the last to be adopted at shelters? We love our black pups and our black cat, even if she might just be a little witchy familiar 😉🖤
.

It’s Beauty Bash Week @hkbknoxville! As a local business (and the only all women plastic surgery office in Knoxville) I’m thrilled and honored to partner with them to bring some awareness to this week full of great specials.
.
But let’s settle in for a quick story shall we? I never used to take care of my skin. No daily sunscreen, barely washed my face, slept in my makeup (GASP, I know y’all. I know.) As someone who never really had skin concerns, I was lazy. And then I had two babies, went through the stress of a house fire, was diagnosed with hypothyroidism and turned 30. Suddenly, my skin was freaking out and I was so self conscious about it. That’s when I started researching skin care routines, finally settled on one and implemented it *every night*. No exceptions! Now my skin is so much healthier and I feel much more confident with or without makeup (usually without cause mom life 🤣). The next step I want to take is to add more in depth skin treatments like the Diamond glow facial (which I got last December) and a small amount of botox in my forehead. For me, skin care routines, treatments and preventative actions aren’t about changing the way I look, but helping me feel like my best self while aging. *steps off soapbox* 😉
.
So this week only @hkbknoxville there’s discounts on the following things (must be purchased this week and used within 6 months): 
.
•20% off skin care and makeup (except for prescriptions)
•20% off Botox and filler
•20% off non surgical skincare procedures like peels etc
•Plus huge giveaways on social media and at the in person event on Thursday!
.
@dr.jessica_walker was kind enough to give me a code to share with y’all. Use Jordan15 when you check out online which gives you the 20% off plus an extra 15% off the most expensive item in your cart! It’s a great time to stock up on skincare, which I’ll be doing along with my fave ColorScience Flex. Here’s to feeling like and being our best selves! 💙💙💙
.

My secret sauce to creating a whimsical, old world Christmas inspired by Little Women? Ribbons, ribbons and more ribbons!
.
Bedeck your tree, your garland, your wreaths, your normal non Christmas decor. Basically, if it’s still, it’s getting a ribbon.
.
I like to used them in the colors of our home (light blue, navy, tan/gold/taupe, cream and burgundy) for a cohesive feel throughout the downstairs.
.
For this look, you’re going to want drape-y ribbons which means go for ones that *aren’t* wired. Look for satin, chiffon, and velvet varieties.
.
I save mine from year to year and then add a few rolls to them each Christmas season. Now go get your Little Women on!
.
